@Node ART2 "STCCG.guide/First Contact/Making First Contact"
@TOC MAIN

    @{b}@{u}First Contact Article@{uu}@{ub}
    @{b}by @{uu}

Here is an interview:

  Making First Contact

  ------------
  Carol Wisely
  Web Publisher
  ------------


  An interview with Bill Martinson of Product
  Development

  Q. It's been a while now since the
     announcement of the new license with
     Paramount. Can you tell us what has been
     happening in PD with regards to development
     of the Star Trek Customizable Card Game?

  A. Well, since we're all Trek fans in
     Product Development, the expanded
     license naturally caused a lot of
     excitement around here, but it also
     posed some challenges. Although the
     negotiations with Paramount had been
     going on for something like half a
     year, PD was not involved in those
     discussions (good thing, too -- the
     suspense would've killed us!). For a
     long time our plans were limited to
     Next Generation concepts and revolved
     around just a few remaining expansion
     sets. After the announcement, many of
     our plans had to be re-formulated to
     encompass more years, more expansions,
     more Star Trek properties etc.

     Of course, lots of new exciting
     options have opened up for us now:
     additional affiliations, a wider
     variety of storyline elements and
     other gameplay threads that were not
     possible using Next Gen cards alone.
     We have been working to map out a
     basic four-year plan for the game.
     This plan includes loads of cool stuff
     from all four of our Star Trek
     properties in a way that reflects the
     unique "feel" of First Contact, Deep
     Space Nine and Voyager. But we also
     want them all to integrate naturally
     into the cards and rules everybody is
     already familiar with. Feedback from
     our customers is divided; some want
     the new properties to basically stand
     alone, while others desire a single,
     unified game system. Our goal is to
     bring out new cards in such a way that
     both approaches are possible when you
     design your deck -- so players can
     "have their gagh and eat it, too."

  Q. Well, we know First Contact will be the
     next major expansion set. What can you tell
     us about it?

  A. First Contact marks the debut of
     two really important changes for the
     Star Trek Customizable Card Game: the
     new Borg affiliation and a new
     expansion pack format.

     Lots of people are very excited about
     the Borg affiliation, but a few have
     expressed concerns about its viability
     as an affiliation, game balance issues
     and consistency with existing Borg
     cards. We considered all these issues
     and more, months ago when we decided
     to make a Borg affiliation, and
     identified ways to overcome the
     hurdles in a manner that befits the
     nature of the Borg Collective. I think
     players will be very pleased.

     The other big change is an improvement
     in the way we print and package the
     cards. We will be using a new
     expansion pack configuration with 1
     rare, 3 uncommon and 5 common cards
     for a total of 9 cards in each pack.
     At a suggested retail price of $2.50
     per expansion pack, this new format is
     designed to make it easier for people
     to complete their sets.

  Q. What do you see as the major benefits of
     such a change?

  A. The main feature of this pack
     design is the lower cost per rare
     card. Many players and collectors
     estimate their costs based solely on
     the rare cards, because by the time
     you have collected all of the rares in
     a set, you usually have all of the
     uncommons and commons automatically.
     From this perspective, the new system
     represents a savings of about 17% per
     rare.

     The trade-off for this lower cost is
     fewer commons in each pack, which for
     the typical player or collector simply
     means fewer unneeded duplicate
     commons.

  Q. Okay. Tell us about the content.

  A. (Warning: if you haven't seen First
     Contact, beware spoilers here!)
     Naturally there will be all the
     obvious cool stuff like the
     Enterprise-E, the first meeting with
     the Vulcans, Zefram Cochrane and the
     Phoenix. And most players already know
     that a Borg affiliation is lurking in
     the shadows. Of course there will also
     be a variety of the usual card types:
     personnel, ships, events, interrupts,
     dilemmas etc. But we also have a
     couple of surprises planned, including
     an interesting "twist" on a familiar
     old card type.

  Q. So what excites you most about the set?

  A. Hmmm, I don't want to spoil
     anything for anybody, but I have to
     admit I'm really anticipating the time
     travel element. We are working on
     different approaches to this time
     travel thread, and the possibilities
     are very exciting.

     There's also going to be a new icon on
     some of the cards that will be a bit
     of a "teaser" for a future enhancement
     that I think will add a new strategic
     element to the game.

  Q. What about the rarity breakdown. Can you
     tell us what it will be?

  A. Our current plans for First Contact
     are based on a 90-card set consisting
     of 40 rares, 25 uncommons and 25
     commons. This new system also
     eliminates "oddities" such as a rare
     card on the uncommon sheet and the
     "4/3" rarity cards on the other
     sheets.

  Q. That's a lot of rares. What effect will
     this have on the collector?

  A. Actually, it's about the same
     number of rares as in previous
     expansion sets; it just seems like a
     lot compared to the other two
     rarities. We estimate that collecting
     a set of First Contact would cost
     approximately 17% less when compared
     to the rarity system used for
     Q-Continuum. (Naturally, this number
     will vary depending on individual
     habits: trading vs. purchasing
     additional packs vs. buying cards on
     the secondary market.)

     To illustrate the improvement, suppose
     a player purchases 40 packs of
     Q-Continuum and 40 packs of First
     Contact. To simplify the comparison,
     assume that the cards are perfectly
     distributed (i.e., no uneven
     duplication). The QC packs cost $120
     and result in 1 of each rare, 3 of
     each uncommon and 11 of each common.
     In contrast, the First Contact packs
     cost only $100 and result in 1 of each
     rare, almost 5 of each uncommon and
     only 8 of each common. So the number
     of rares is about the same, you get
     one or two extra copies of each
     uncommon and fewer unneeded copies of
     all the commons -- all for less money!
     (Granted, this simple example assumes
     a perfectly "flat" probability
     distribution of individual cards,
     whereas in reality there is usually
     some duplication of rares. However,
     this statistical duplication is a
     given in both packaging systems, so
     the relative savings for the new
     system still apply.)

     With lower pack costs, more rares for
     your money and the elimination of
     "4/3" rarities, we hope that this
     change will be an improvement for
     players and collectors alike.

  Q. Now I know you cannot release details of
     any sets beyond First Contact at this time,
     but what single thing excites you the most
     about the future of this particular CCG?

  A. Yikes, it's really hard to pin down
     one thing. Like most players, we
     designers have our own "dream cards"
     and "dream concepts." There have been
     things we've wanted to do for a long
     time that were not possible under our
     previous license. I guess two things
     come immediately to mind: First, our
     new license creates the potential for
     some brand-new affiliations with
     interesting strengths and weaknesses,
     which opens up exciting new deck
     strategies and gameplay possibilities
     and which also enhances multi-player
     games quite a bit. (Two of the new
     affiliations will make a brief debut
     in the First Anthology.) Second, the
     inclusion of our three new Star Trek
     properties promises to have a profound
     effect on the spaceline. I'm very
     excited about the new strategies that
     will develop when that happens.

@EndNode

@Node ART3 "STCCG.guide/First Contact/The Strategy of Hidden Agenda Cards"
@TOC MAIN

    @{b}@{u}The Strategy of Hidden Agenda Cards@{uu}@{ub}

  With new cards, comes new strategies!
  Sandy Wible outlines important details
  about Hidden Agenda Cards below.

  Make sure you check out the previous
  article entitled Phasers: Don't Get
  Caught Without One!.

  @{b}The Strategy of Hidden Agenda Cards@{ub}

  ------------
  by Sandy Wible
  ------------

  One of the new strategies introduced
  in First Contact is implemented by a
  new "hidden agenda" icon on some
  cards, usually Event or Objective
  cards. This icon looks like a small
  card back, and appears on the left of
  the title bar, in the same position as
  the Alternate Universe symbol has
  appeared on previous cards.

  The rules sheet explains how this icon
  works. Basically, cards with this icon
  represent secret objectives or other
  clandestine strategies. When you play
  such a card, you announce it as a
  hidden agenda card and place it face
  down on the table without showing it
  to your opponent (this counts as your
  normal card play). While face down,
  its identity is concealed and thus it
  is immune to general-use cards such as
  Kevin Uxbridge. In fact, your opponent
  doesn't know what card type it is!

  You may activate a hidden agenda card
  by turning it face up at any time,
  even as a response to another action.
  This immediately activates the card's
  game text. If there are any conditions
  specified by the card, you must meet
  them at this time (if you cannot, you
  must immediately turn the card face
  down again). Once activated, the card
  remains face up until removed from
  play.

  Some hidden agenda cards may be seeded
  (they say so in their game text, such
  as "Seeds or plays on table") and thus
  it's your choice as to how you want to
  play them. You can spend a seed card
  slot, or else spend a card draw and a
  card play. Sometimes you might even
  want to do both: seed a copy of a
  specific hidden agenda card as well as
  stock one or two of that card in your
  deck or Q's Tent.

  Bluffing using hidden agenda cards is
  very cool. When you seed or play one,
  your opponent has absolutely no idea
  what gameplay twist is hiding and
  awaiting for that critical situation!
  Your opponent never knows whether you
  will reveal your hidden agenda card to
  penalize a particular card play, or
  perhaps to surprise his attacking Away
  Team with your Prepare Assault Teams
  objective. Timing is also important
  with these cards. When and how you
  reveal them can drastically affect
  their result. For example, a hidden
  agenda card that affects both players
  is a double-bladed sword, penalizing a
  specific card or strategy no matter
  which player is taking a turn. Wait
  until your opponent tries to get away
  with it before you reveal the card,
  and thus postpone affecting yourself
  until the last possible moment. In
  addition, you may wish to wait and
  hurt your opponent more, but waiting
  too long might be disastrous! Above
  all, these cards are a wonderful tool
  which add a great deal of strategy
  with the simple elegance of a short
  rule and icon. Enjoy playing with
  them!

@EndNode

@Node ART4 "STCCG.guide/First Contact/Duty, Honor and Glory"
@TOC MAIN

    @{b}@{u}Duty, Honor and Glory@{uu}@{ub}

  Personnel battle rules, new in First
  Contact, are addressed in this
  article.


  Duty, Honor and Glory

  ------------
  by Tim Ellington,
  Game Designer
  ------------

  note: Star Trek CCG cards are in
  italics

  Your Klingons are trapped on Valt
  Minor. Two turns, two Borg attacks.
  You've taken down several Borg drones
  in glorious battle, but two of your
  warriors have been assimilated. Your
  opponent is wearing you down. But this
  turn, you've got a surprise. He will
  rue the day he took on the Klingon
  Empire...

  First Contact [TM], the latest
  expansion set of the Star Trek [TM]
  Customizable Card Game [TM],
  introduces new personnel battle rules
  designed to add more realism - and
  more interaction - to the STCCG
  universe. New and existing cards
  accentuate the new gameplay by adding
  an unpredictable element to personnel
  battles. Interrupts, equipment,
  attribute enhancements, timing and a
  little bit of luck combine to give new
  depth to this aspect of the game.

  Your leader has been mortally wounded,
  two security officers lie stunned
  beside him. You play Klingon Right of
  Vengeance and dream of the songs that
  will be sung in their honor. The
  Klingon Empire will NEVER yield!

  Abduction. Nerve pinches. Headlocks.
  Phaser burns. Assimilation. All these
  elements combine to take personnel
  battles to a new level of complexity,
  where your Away Team forces engage
  adversaries in a version of
  hand-to-hand combat that is sure to
  add excitement and interaction. Cards
  like Mission Debriefing, which can
  stop an Away Team on a planet, allow
  players more opportunity to attack
  opposing forces on planets. Other
  cards target personnel for
  assimilation and even allow beaming
  through shields to attack opposing
  crews. And the introduction of the
  Borg means Federation forces now have
  an affiliation they can attack at
  will.

  You were stopped by Lack of
  Preparation. An Away Team of Romulans
  attack. They have several Non-Aligned
  personnel carrying the powerful new
  Starfleet Type III Phaser Rifles.
  Those sneaky Romulans. With that added
  firepower, the Romulan forces kill
  half your Away Team. Will
  reinforcements get there in time?

  Many of the new cards in First Contact
  have obvious battle-related elements
  designed into their gameplay. Many
  Borg drones were designed with special
  skills that make the Borg an
  affiliation to be feared. Drones such
  as Eight of Nineteen, which allows
  your Borg present to gain Strength +2,
  are universal and can be used in
  tandem with other drones to amass a
  formidable Away Team. Other drones
  work better in ship battles, where
  they can force your Romulan Warbird to
  decloak and take the brute force of
  the Borg Cube's 24 weapons. Yes, the
  Borg are powerful, but they are also
  single-minded. The successful player
  will use cunning and agility to avoid
  the Borg and complete his missions.

  Your turn. Humuhumunukunukuapua'a
  looks innocent enough when you play it
  at the start of your turn. But then
  you play Disruptor Overload, announce
  a counter-attack, play Phaser Burns
  and grin as your opponent starts to do
  the math. A successful counter leaves
  his Romulans reeling. He doesn't
  gamble on his turn, and beams his
  decimated forces back to his ship and
  leaves while he still can.

  New weapons such as Tommygun,
  Starfleet Type III Phaser Rifle and
  Antique Machine Gun give Away Teams
  more firepower. Other cards, such as
  Prepare Assault Teams and Android
  Headlock, combine with the new
  "downloading" feature to get valuable
  cards into play lightning fast.
  Downloading allows you to access
  certain cards immediately from your
  draw deck, Q's Tent or hand, even as a
  response to an attack. Nothing is a
  sure thing anymore. Are you sure
  you're ready to take a chance? What
  are you going to do when the Borg are
  about to assimilate your Homeworld and
  your only option is to fight?

  The Borg have beamed onto your ship.
  They want a counterpart. You Prepare
  Assault Teams to protect their target
  - your captain! As the adversaries
  engage one-by-one, you hold your
  breath. There he is! Your captain
  pairs with a drone and is immediately
  abducted and beamed back to the Borg
  ship. After the battle, you check your
  crew. There's only one thing to do.
  You beam over to the cube and attack.
  It's the only way to save your
  captain, and your Homeworld!

  First Contact brings a new feel to
  Star Trek Customizable Card Game. New
  personnel battle rules mean more
  battles and a higher level of player
  interaction that allow bold, creative
  gameplay. In addition to the new cards
  in this set, the new gameplay makes
  existing cards much more valuable.
  Phasers? Disruptors? Don't get caught
  without one. And the clever player
  will make use of new cards to get
  important tactical information
  necessary to ensure victory. But be
  careful. Everything is not as obvious
  as an angry drone.

  Your Away Team announces a mission
  attempt. You see the first dilemma.
  Suddenly there are four Rogue Borg on
  your bridge, and you know there are
  more coming. But they don't
  immediately attack! What do you do...?

@EndNode

@Node ART5 "STCCG.guide/First Contact/All-Space Decks Beware!"
@TOC MAIN

    @{b}@{u}All-Space Decks Beware!@{uu}@{ub}

  All-Space Decks Beware!

  ------------
  by Bill Martinson,
  Lead Game Designer, Star Trek CCG
  ------------


  One of the design goals of the First
  Contact expansion set was to
  revitalize underused cards (sometimes
  called "binder fodder") from previous
  sets. To achieve this goal using a
  minimum number of new cards (thus
  saving more card slots for other new
  gameplay possibilities), we tried to
  identify groups of cards that suffered
  from the same drawbacks, and thus
  could be enhanced in one fell swoop.
  Mission specialists are probably the
  best example of this.

  Two other groups of cards that
  sometimes lack popularity are
  planet-only and space-only dilemmas.
  Because many players tend to use six
  planet missions or six space missions,
  putting a space- or planet-specific
  dilemma in your deck involves a
  certain amount of risk that it won't
  affect your opponent, other than as a
  mis-seeded "bluff" card. The solution,
  naturally, was to encourage players to
  use a mixture of planet and space
  missions via the new Balancing Act
  card. This dilemma creates a strong
  disincentive to using five or six
  missions of the same type.

  Balancing Act makes it safe again to
  use your creativity with the full
  power of all your existing dilemmas.
  (For example, consider the combo
  possibilities offered by the new
  planet dilemma Blended.) One strategy
  is to build two planet-only dilemma
  combos, two space-only combos, and two
  "either" combos. If your opponent's
  mix of planet and space missions is
  2/4, 3/3 or 4/2, all your dilemmas
  will be 100% applicable to those
  missions. On the other hand, if he
  uses 5 or 6 missions of the same type,
  some of your dilemmas will be just
  "bluff" cards, but your Balancing Act
  will cost him 50 points! (See the
  Balancing Act card extra for some
  ideas on where to seed this card.)
  Losing that many points will probably
  require him to do two more missions
  than he'd planned on, severely slowing
  down his deck.

  So if you're tired of facing those
  all-space speed decks, blow the dust
  off some of your planet and space
  dilemmas and make your opponents face
  some new hazards -- as well as some
  old ones they haven't seen for a
  couple of years!

@EndNode

@Node ART6 "STCCG.guide/First Contact/Playing With Only First Contact Cards"
@TOC MAIN

    @{b}@{u}Playing With Only First Contact Cards@{uu}@{ub}
    @{b}by Kevin Allen, aka Phoenix@{uu}

  "This changes everything."

  It's true. First Contact's many changes, fixes,
  and enhancements impact the game in a big way.
  The new Star Trek CCG expansion is attracting
  new players, and drawing back old players -
  like me - who had left the game. No matter
  which of these camps you fall into, it's likely
  that many of your Star Trek CCG cards are from
  the First Contact expansion. Here are some
  strategies for putting together an effective
  deck composed almost entirely of First Contact
  cards. Cards from other Star Trek CCG sets will
  be required, but my intention is to show how
  you can be competitive using just First
  Contact.

  The first issue is affiliation. If you've got
  First Contact cards only to draw from, you'll
  pretty much be playing Borg. It's possible to
  put together a Federation deck, but Fed-only
  would have some severe handicaps. Klingons and
  Romulans you can forget about. Remember - this
  is geared towards allowing you to use those
  shiny new First Contact cards without having to
  buy a lot of others.

  Since the Borg are the only true stand-alone
  affiliation in the new expansion, that's what
  you're limited too. Come on, be assimilated,
  and take some analgesic creme - those implants
  can cause severe skin irritation. If you're
  going to be playing Borg, trade for all you're
  worth to get those Queens. Though every other
  Borg card can be worked around, she is so vital
  (and helpful) to a Borg deck as to be nearly
  mandatory.

  The second thing to consider is which cards you
  absolutely MUST get from outside First Contact
  in order to play. The missions in First Contact
  are good, but you can't build a whole deck
  around them. Fortunately, between the premium
  Warp Packs and judicious singles purchases, you
  should be in good shape. Keep in mind that
  we're playing Borg. Look for a variety of
  missions, what is required, and who can attempt
  them. Remember that you won't be attempting
  missions, so vary who can, as well as what is
  needed to complete them. It's also a good idea
  to look for Expose Covert Supply and Cloaked
  Mission, as these are the homeworld missions
  for the Romulans and Klingons. Add the
  Espionage Mission from FC, and you've got
  homeworld targets no matter what your opponent
  is playing. Remember that since each homeworld
  mission is only attemptable by an enemy, it is
  unlikely that your opponent will have them in
  his deck.

  Fortunately, both the above missions are only
  Uncommon, and should be easy to find on the
  singles market.

  Not as central as the missions, but still
  necessary, are the other general- use cards.
  Q's-Tent and an AU doorway are pretty
  important, though you can skip the AU unless
  you're playing for the Stop First Contact.
  Others to consider are Kivas Fajo - Collector,
  Masaka Transformations, and Yellow Alert. These
  general use cards can help any deck out. Use
  them correctly, and to your advantage.

  Third, and most devastating, is the dilemma
  issue. While First Contact does have some
  powerful dilemmas, including Primitive Culture,
  Theta Radiation Poisoning, and Strict Dress
  Code, they are limited. Many of them focus on
  dealing with gameplay issues, and are not real
  power-stoppers on their own. You will
  definitely need to pick up some earlier
  dilemmas. Look for ones that combine with the
  dilemmas you have. Chinese Finger Puzzle
  leading into a Shot In The Back is nice, and
  Don't Call Me Ahab followed by a Conundrum can
  be devastating. A Male Love Interest can leave
  a Counterpart target all by his lonesome at the
  far end of the spaceline, just waiting for the
  Queen to claim her mate.

  First Contact has brought new life to Star Trek
  with greater speed than any of us could have
  imagined. While those of us who sold all our
  cards weep over that fact when we're alone at
  night, it's not an insurmountable obstacle.
  With some creative combos, and selective
  singles purchases, you can be the powerful
  terror you once were.

@EndNode

